text.tspan: A - Agribusiness feeds cities and does so with incredible
efficiency. That industry is moving toward larger and more
autonomous machines.
B - The vast majority of people prefer to live in cities.
Densification, often along commuter rail lines, allows city
populations to increase without encroaching on farmland.
C - Agribusiness and cities are, however, large emitters of
CO2. As the climate warms some farmland and forests may
be put at risk or lost each year to desertification, fires, and
erosion.
Feedback loops from damaged soil can accelerate future
land loss, it can worsen city heat islanding effects, and it can
diminish water supplies.
D - Small carbon-negative agro-forestry households on land-
at-risk can halt degradation and then restore habitat while
providing a carbon sink. That can mitigate feedback loops.
The Hundred-Year-Farm project is developing technology
and practices that could perhaps be used some day to help
balance competing demands for housing, land, water, and
habitat.
